==English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|acousticks}} {{qualifier|obsolete}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr|en}} {{m|fr|acoustique}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|ἀκουστικός}}, from {{m|grc|ἀκούω||to hear}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/əˈkuːstɪks/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-acoustics.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}
See [[-ics]] regarding the treatment of such nouns as singular.

# The physical quality of a space for conveying [[sound]].
#: ''Until they discovered the non-contractual [[concrete]] slab under the stage floor, everyone at [[Wikipedia:Carnegie Hall|Carnegie Hall]] wondered, since the renovations, why the '''acoustics''' had changed.''
# {{lb|en|physics}} The [[science]] of [[sound]]s, teaching their [[nature]], [[phenomena]] and [[laws]].
#: '''Acoustics''', then, or the science of sound, is a very considerable branch of physics. - Sir [[Wikipedia:John Herschel|John Herschel]].

====Usage notes====
* The science was previously divided by some writers into [[diacoustics]], which explains the properties of sounds coming directly from (''sic!'' Webster) the ear; and [[catacoustica]], which treats of reflected sounds or echoes. This division is now obsolete.

